  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 1-22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - 3. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Third admonitory discourse, pointing out the benefits which arise from a sincere, earnest, and persevering search after Wisdom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This discourse divides itself into three parts. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Vers. 1-9: a statement of the conditions which, if fulfilled, result in the highest knowledge of Jehovah - the fear of Jehovah and the knowledge of God, who is the Source of wisdom and the Protection and Ensurer of safety to the righteous. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Vers. 10-19: the negatively beneficial results of Wisdom, in delivery from the paths of evil, from destructive lusts and passions, from the temptations of wicked men and wicked women. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(3)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Vers. 20-22: the epilogue, or conclusion, combining encouragement on the one hand, and warning on the other. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 1.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The teacher here reverts to the original form of his address, as appears from the employment of the term, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "my son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It seems clear that it is no longer Wisdom personified who is the speaker, from the fact that the words, \"wisdom and understanding\" in ver. 2 are used without the possessive pronoun \"my,\" which would have been undoubtedly inserted if this address had been a continuation of the discourse in the preceding chapter. Some of the ideas of that address, however, are restated, as the crying and lifting up the voice after Wisdom, and the  conclusion, wherein the respective destinies of the pious and wicked are portrayed. The particle \"if\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֵם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is conditional, and serves to introduce the series of clauses (vers. 1-4) which lay down the conditions upon which the promises depend, and which form the protasis to the double apodosis in vers. 5 and 9. De Wette, Meyer, and Delitzsch regard it as voluntative, as expressing a wish on the part of the teacher, and translate, \"Oh that thou wouldst!\" and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אִם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"if,\" is used in this way in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 139:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; but the LXX. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐάν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and Vulgate (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "si",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") make it conditional. It is repeated in an emphatic form in ver. 3. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Receive",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The verbs \"receive\" and \"hide\" show that the endeavour after Wisdom is to be candid and sincere. \"To receive\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לָקַה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") seems to be here used, like the LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δεχέσθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the sense of \"to receive graciously,\" \"to admit the words of Wisdom.\" It is noticeable that there is a gradation in emphasis in the various terms here used by the teacher. Just as \"commandments\" is stronger than \"words,\" so \"hide\" is stronger than \"receive.\" The emphasizing is carried on in the following verses in the same way, and at length culminates in ver. 4, which sums up the ardent spirit in which the search after Wisdom is to be prosecuted in presenting it to us in its strongest form. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hide",
        "children": []
      },
      {
